# Rent vs. Buy FAQ: 115 Research-Backed Questions

## How to use this FAQ

This FAQ supports an interactive rent-vs-buy financial simulation tool. Questions are organized into 10 sections matching the most common areas of user confusion, criticism, and debate. Each answer is 2–4 sentences with citations where available. Tool-specific features are referenced in **[brackets]** where relevant. Use Ctrl+F to search by keyword.

---

## 1. Common criticisms of rent-vs-buy calculators

**Q1. Why do different rent-vs-buy calculators give wildly different answers for the same inputs?**
A Wall Street Journal test found that for identical inputs on a $320K home, Freddie Mac projected $56.6K in buyer savings, NerdWallet showed $76K, and Realtor.com showed $95K — a nearly 2.5× spread. This happens because calculators embed different hidden assumptions about tax treatment, opportunity cost, and which costs to include. The tool addresses this with full transparency: every assumption is editable, and the **[verdict confidence system]** (🟢🟡🔴) tells you whether the result is robust to reasonable variation.

**Q2. Are most rent-vs-buy calculators biased toward buying?**
Yes. The National Multifamily Housing Council (NMHC) conducted a systematic review and found "most are seriously flawed, with a bias toward ownership." They noted that all reviewed products were designed to help renters decide whether to buy — none helped owners evaluate whether they should rent instead. Common biases include overstating tax benefits, understating maintenance, and ignoring the opportunity cost of the down payment.

**Q3. Why are results so sensitive to small assumption changes?**
Because the calculation compounds over decades, a 1-percentage-point change in home appreciation or investment returns can shift the outcome by tens of thousands of dollars. The **[sensitivity tornado]** in this tool shows exactly how much each variable moves the needle, ranked by impact. Academic research consistently shows that appreciation rate, investment return, and time horizon dominate all other variables.

**Q4. Do these calculators properly account for the opportunity cost of the down payment?**
Most simple calculators ignore that a $60K–$200K+ down payment could be invested in stocks or index funds. The Independent Institute built their calculator specifically to address this: "These calculators greatly underestimate the opportunity costs of the road not taken." This tool models the full opportunity cost by having the **[renter invest the down payment equivalent]** from month one.

**Q5. Don't these tools just tell people what they want to hear based on the assumptions they plug in?**
This is the most universal criticism — "garbage in, garbage out." The solution is not to trust any single scenario but to stress-test assumptions. This tool's **[12 preset scenarios]** provide research-grounded starting points, and the **[sensitivity tornado]** reveals which assumptions actually matter. The **[verdict confidence system]** explicitly flags when the result is 🔴 Highly assumption-dependent.

**Q6. Why don't calculators show a range of outcomes instead of a single number?**
Most consumer calculators give a single deterministic answer, which creates false precision. The NMHC compared this to retirement planning where "it is useful to consider a range of possibilities." This tool uses the **[sensitivity tornado]** to show the range of plausible outcomes across each variable, helping users understand the full distribution of possibilities.

**Q7. Are the default assumptions in most calculators accurate for my local market?**
Rarely. A Bogleheads user found that "Zillow and Redfin's assumptions for property taxes are just straight-up wrong in Miami-Dade County — it's 2.1%, not the massively lower numbers they use." Insurance defaults are similarly unreliable, especially in climate-affected states. This tool includes **[54 metro-specific sourced data defaults]** to address this, but users should always verify local inputs.

**Q8. Do calculators account for rising property taxes, insurance, and maintenance over time?**
Many simple calculators treat these costs as fixed, which the NMHC specifically flagged as a major flaw. In reality, property taxes rise with assessed value, insurance premiums have surged 24% from 2021–2024 (Consumer Federation of America), and maintenance costs escalate with home age. Good models inflate these annually — this tool does so based on the appreciation and inflation assumptions.

**Q9. Why don't calculators capture the time and labor costs of homeownership?**
No calculator quantifies the hundreds of hours homeowners spend on maintenance, repairs, yard work, and renovation projects. As one Bogleheads user noted: "Time working on a house could be spent starting another business or doing things you enjoy." This is a genuine limitation — the tool captures financial costs but cannot assign a dollar value to personal time preferences.

**Q10. Isn't comparing a 1-bedroom rental to a 3-bedroom house an apples-to-oranges problem?**
Yes, and it is one of the most common analytical errors. Kellogg professor Craig Furfine (2025) showed that when comparing truly identical properties, the result in efficient markets tends toward indifference between renting and buying. This tool's **[monthly-payment-first architecture]** helps by anchoring on what you'd actually spend, but users should ensure they're comparing equivalent living situations.

**Q11. Can I trust a calculator made by a mortgage lender or real estate company?**
Be cautious. The NMHC found systematic pro-ownership bias in calculators hosted by industry players. Lender-hosted tools have a financial incentive to show buying is favorable. This tool is independent — it has no commercial affiliation with lenders, realtors, or rental platforms, and every assumption is user-editable and transparent.

**Q12. Why does the time horizon matter so much more than any other input?**
Transaction costs of 8–10% of home value must be amortized over the holding period. If you stay 5 years, those costs eat 1.6–2% per year of returns; at 20 years, only 0.4–0.5%. The Bogleheads wiki states plainly: "If you do not know if you will be in a property for more than 5 years, there is no financial advantage to owning." The tool models this month by month with **[month-precise amortization]**.

