## 2. Investment return assumptions

**Q13. Should I use 10%, 7%, or some other number for stock market returns?**
The ~10% figure is the long-term nominal compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of the S&P 500 from Ibbotson/SBBI data (1926–present). After inflation, it is ~7%. The arithmetic average is ~12%. For a rent-vs-buy model, **7% nominal** (or ~4% real) is a defensible moderate assumption, as forward-looking estimates from Vanguard, BlackRock, and Morningstar cluster around 5–7% nominal for the next decade.

**Q14. What is the difference between arithmetic and geometric mean returns, and why does it matter here?**
The arithmetic mean is the simple average of annual returns; the geometric mean (CAGR) reflects actual compounded growth. With any volatility, geometric is always lower — the gap is approximately σ²/2 (~2 percentage points for stocks). Jacquier, Kane, and Marcus (2003, *Financial Analysts Journal*) showed that using arithmetic means for long-term projections creates upwardly biased forecasts that can differ by more than a factor of 2 at 40-year horizons.

**Q15. What is volatility drag, and does it affect my calculation?**
Volatility drag (or "variance drain," coined by Messmore, 1995, *Journal of Portfolio Management*) is the reduction in compound returns caused by fluctuations, approximated as σ²/2. For a portfolio with 15–20% standard deviation, the drag is about 1–2 percentage points. If the tool's investment return input represents a CAGR (geometric return), volatility drag is already embedded — no further adjustment is needed.

**Q16. Why does Vanguard project only 3–5% for US stocks when the historical average is 10%?**
Vanguard's Capital Markets Model (VCMM, Nov 2024) projects 2.8–4.8% nominal for US equities over the next 10 years. This is driven by elevated starting valuations — the Shiller CAPE ratio is strongly predictive of subsequent 10–20 year returns. Notably, international stocks are projected at 6.9–8.9%. Over 30+ year horizons, returns tend to mean-revert closer to historical averages (Kitces, 2016).

**Q17. What does Aswath Damodaran's research say about expected returns?**
Damodaran (NYU Stern) computes both historical and implied equity risk premiums. His implied ERP at the start of 2026 was 4.23% over US Treasury bonds, suggesting total expected equity returns of roughly 8.5–9%. He warns that the historical ERP of 5.4–7.0% comes with a standard error of 2.12%, creating a massive confidence interval, and advocates for implied (forward-looking) premiums over historical ones.

**Q18. What does Michael Kitces recommend for return assumptions?**
Kitces recommends a "regime-based" approach: project below-average returns for the first 10–15 years when starting valuations are high, then higher returns as valuations revert. He cautions against uniformly reducing long-term averages by a small amount, as this understates near-term risk while overstating long-term pessimism. In high-valuation environments, reducing equity return assumptions by ~1 percentage point below historical averages is reasonable.

**Q19. Should I use historical returns or forward-looking estimates?**
Forward-looking returns are more defensible but harder to pin down. Ed Easterling (Crestmont Research/AAII) showed the commonly cited 10% nominal figure is inflated by the low starting P/E of 10.2 in 1926 — had the sample started at a P/E of ~20, the average would be closer to 7%. A reasonable compromise: use 6–7% nominal, which accounts for forward-looking expectations, portfolio diversification, and investment costs/taxes.

**Q20. What return should I assume if my renter portfolio isn't 100% stocks?**
A balanced 60/40 portfolio has historically returned roughly 8–9% nominal (5–6% real), versus 10% for all-equity. Ben Felix (PWL Capital) uses 6.57% nominal based on a blend of historical and forward-looking P/E-based estimates. If investments are in taxable accounts, reduce by another 0.5–1% for annual tax drag on dividends and realized gains. The tool allows you to set this to whatever reflects your actual investment strategy.

**Q21. Don't average investors earn much less than index returns?**
Yes. DALBAR research consistently shows the average equity fund investor earns 2–4 percentage points less than the index due to poor timing (buying high, selling low). This behavioral shortfall is separate from the theoretical return debate and further weakens the "rent and invest" assumption. The tool's **[renter discipline slider]** (30–100%) directly addresses this by letting you model realistic investor behavior.

**Q22. How does the 1926 start date bias historical return statistics?**
The S&P 500's 1926 starting P/E of 10.2 was unusually low — essentially a near-bottom valuation. Over the subsequent 95+ years, P/E ratios expanded to 20–30+, contributing roughly 0.5–1% per year to returns from valuation expansion alone. This one-time tailwind won't repeat from today's elevated valuations. Ed Easterling (AAII) estimates the "true" long-run equity return is closer to 7% nominal absent this starting-point effect.

