## 3. Tax treatment questions

**Q23. How did the 2017 TCJA change the mortgage interest deduction?**
The TCJA reduced the deductible mortgage cap from $1 million to $750,000, eliminated home equity interest deductions (unless used for home improvement), nearly doubled the standard deduction, and capped SALT deductions at $10,000. The share of returns claiming the mortgage interest deduction fell from 31% in 2017 to 11% in 2018 (Tax Policy Center). Pre-December 2017 mortgages were grandfathered at the old $1M limit.

**Q24. How many taxpayers actually benefit from the mortgage interest deduction today?**
Only about 9–11% of taxpayers now itemize, down from ~31% before TCJA (IRS data via Congressional Research Service). The remaining ~90% take the standard deduction and receive zero tax benefit from mortgage interest. Even among itemizers, higher-income households capture roughly 71% of the total deduction value (Joint Committee on Taxation).

**Q25. What is the "excess itemization" concept, and why is it so important?**
Only the portion of total itemized deductions that exceeds the standard deduction produces any tax savings. If a married couple has a $31,500 standard deduction (2025) and $28,000 in itemized deductions, their mortgage interest provides zero additional benefit. This tool uses the **[post-TCJA excess itemization method]** — the only correct approach — rather than the naive method of multiplying all mortgage interest by the marginal tax rate.

**Q26. Can you give a concrete example of excess itemization?**
A married couple with $20,000 mortgage interest, $10,000 SALT (at cap), and $5,000 charity has $35,000 total itemized deductions. Against a $31,500 standard deduction (2025), only the $3,500 excess generates savings — at a 24% marginal rate, that is $840/year in tax benefit. A naive calculation would show $20,000 × 24% = $4,800 — overstating the benefit by 5.7×. The tool computes this correctly.

**Q27. What is the current standard deduction?**
For 2025 (post-OBBBA): $15,750 single, $31,500 married filing jointly, $23,625 head of household. For 2026: $16,100 / $32,200 / $24,150 respectively. These thresholds are high enough that most homeowners — especially those with mortgages under ~$400K — cannot exceed them with itemized deductions alone.

**Q28. What is the Section 121 capital gains exclusion?**
When selling a primary residence, you can exclude up to $250,000 (single) or $500,000 (married filing jointly) of capital gains from taxation. You must have owned and lived in the home for at least 2 of the prior 5 years. There is no lifetime limit — it can be used once every 2 years. This is one of the largest tax advantages of homeownership and is modeled in the tool.

**Q29. What is the SALT cap and how does it affect property tax deductions?**
The SALT (State and Local Tax) deduction was capped at $10,000 from 2018–2024, raised to $40,000 for 2025–2029 (with income phase-down starting at $500K MAGI), and reverts to $10,000 in 2030. In high-tax states like New Jersey (median property tax ~$9,767), property taxes alone can approach the cap, limiting the federal deductibility of ownership costs. The tool accounts for this cap in its **[excess itemization calculation]**.

**Q30. How do unrealized vs. realized capital gains affect the comparison?**
Both homeowners and stock investors hold unrealized gains until they sell. Homeowners get the massive Section 121 exclusion ($250K/$500K tax-free), while renters pay 0–23.8% capital gains tax on stock profits. However, renters can time their sales and use tax-loss harvesting, while homeowners must sell the entire house to access equity. Both asset classes receive a stepped-up basis at death.

**Q31. Does the mortgage interest deduction actually promote homeownership?**
Research consistently says no. Studies by Glaeser and Shapiro, Sommer and Sullivan, and Gruber et al. (NBER) find the deduction does not increase homeownership rates — it primarily encourages purchase of larger, more expensive homes and increases household debt. OECD research concludes it becomes "partly capitalised in house prices" and is "largely ineffective in improving housing accessibility."

**Q32. Are the TCJA tax provisions permanent?**
The OBBBA (2025) made the $750K mortgage interest limit and the doubled standard deduction permanent. The SALT cap was raised to $40,000 through 2029 but reverts to $10,000 in 2030. These are the current law provisions modeled by the tool, but future legislation could change them. The **[fully editable custom panel]** lets users adjust tax assumptions for any scenario.

**Q33. How should I handle taxes on the renter's investment portfolio in the model?**
Stock investments in taxable accounts face annual tax drag on dividends (~1.5–2% yield × tax rate) and eventual capital gains taxes when sold. Tax-advantaged accounts (401k, IRA) defer or eliminate these taxes but have contribution limits and withdrawal restrictions. The tool's investment return input should reflect after-tax expected returns if the renter invests in taxable accounts, or pre-tax if using retirement accounts.

---

## 4. Behavioral finance and renter discipline

**Q34. Do renters actually invest the savings difference between rent and a mortgage payment?**
Almost never in practice. The Bernstein and Koudijs (2024, *Quarterly Journal of Economics*) study found that when Dutch households were forced to amortize mortgages, they accumulated wealth at nearly a 1:1 ratio — by cutting consumption, not by reducing other savings. This implies that without the forced mechanism, households consume rather than invest the surplus. Only about 50% of US households own any stocks at all (Federal Reserve SCF, 2019), with much lower participation among renters.

**Q35. What is the "forced savings" effect of mortgage payments?**
Mortgage amortization is one of the most powerful wealth-building mechanisms available because it is automatic and psychologically non-negotiable. Bernstein and Koudijs (2024) showed that mandatory amortization produces wealth accumulation close to $1 for every $1 of forced payment, even five years later. US households contribute $250–300 billion annually through mortgage amortization — comparable in magnitude to all 401(k) contributions combined (~$398 billion).

**Q36. What is the renter discipline slider, and why does the tool include it?**
The **[renter discipline slider]** (30–100%) lets you model what percentage of the savings difference the renter actually invests. At 100%, the renter invests every dollar of surplus — the theoretical ideal. At 30%, only 30% gets invested. The Bernstein-Koudijs finding that forced savings produces near-1:1 wealth accumulation, while voluntary savings does not, directly motivated this feature. Setting it below 100% reflects the behavioral reality for most renters.

**Q37. What should I set the renter discipline slider to?**
There is no universal answer, but evidence suggests 100% is unrealistic for most people. If you have automated investment systems (auto-transfers to index funds, employer retirement plans), 70–90% may be reasonable. If you would invest manually and sporadically, 30–50% is more realistic. The tool lets you see how sensitive the result is to this assumption — often, dropping from 100% to 70% flips the verdict from "rent" to "buy."

**Q38. Is the 40:1 wealth gap between homeowners and renters really caused by homeownership?**
The Federal Reserve's 2019 Survey of Consumer Finances shows median homeowner net worth of $255,000 vs. $6,300 for renters. However, this largely reflects selection effects — wealthier, older, more financially stable households are more likely to buy. The forced savings mechanism contributes, but income, education, financial literacy, and lifecycle stage differ significantly between the groups. Causation and correlation are difficult to disentangle.

**Q39. How does loss aversion affect home-selling decisions?**
Genesove and Mayer (2001, *Quarterly Journal of Economics*) showed that sellers facing nominal losses set asking prices 25–35% above expected selling prices and take significantly longer to sell. Kahneman and Tversky's prospect theory (1979) explains this: losses feel roughly twice as painful as equivalent gains. This makes homeowners reluctant to sell at fair market prices during downturns, reducing mobility and sometimes leading to worse financial outcomes.

**Q40. Why do homeowners consistently overestimate their home's appreciation?**
People cite nominal price gains without deducting property taxes (~1%), maintenance (1–2%), insurance, and transaction costs (5–6% on sale). Leverage creates an illusion: a 4% home appreciation on a 20% down payment looks like a 20% return on equity. Inflation masking is also powerful — a home bought for $200K and sold for $400K after 20 years looks like 100% gain, but at 3% inflation, the real gain is far smaller. US Census data shows homeowners report ~2% real appreciation when the Case-Shiller index shows only ~0.7%.

**Q41. How does the endowment effect distort housing valuations?**
Homeowners systematically overvalue their property simply because they own it (Kahneman, Knetsch, and Thaler, 1991, *Journal of Economic Perspectives*). Multiple reference points — purchase price, renovation costs, neighborhood perceptions — compound this effect. A 2024 study by Tomal in *Real Estate Management and Valuation* confirmed this bias persists in housing markets specifically. This leads to overpriced listings and longer time-on-market.

**Q42. What are the most common emotional errors in the rent-vs-buy decision?**
The biggest are: social pressure to own ("keeping up with the Joneses" — Fannie Mae found 67% cite lifestyle, not financial, reasons to buy); anchoring on mortgage-vs-rent payment instead of total costs; FOMO in hot markets leading to overbidding; overstating tax benefits; and ignoring the opportunity cost of a six-figure down payment. Ben Felix's core insight is that comparing mortgage payment to rent is "a mathematically flawed way to think about it."

**Q43. Is rent really "throwing money away"?**
This is widely considered a myth by financial planners. Homeowners also "throw away" money on mortgage interest (85% of early payments), property taxes, insurance, maintenance, HOA fees, and transaction costs — none of which build equity. As one Bogleheads commenter summarized: "Rent is the ceiling of what you'll pay for housing per month; with buying, the mortgage is just the floor." A 30-year study by the Financial Planning Association (1984–2013) found "the optimal decision was not always homeownership."

---

## 5. Housing market assumptions

**Q44. What is the real (inflation-adjusted) return on housing historically?**
Robert Shiller's data shows long-run real home price appreciation of approximately **0–1% per year** (~0.7% from 1940–present). His famous chart demonstrates a "remarkable tendency for real home prices to return to their 1890 level." Nominal returns of 3–4% per year largely reflect inflation, not real wealth creation. Individual markets deviate substantially from this average.

**Q45. What does the Case-Shiller index show recently?**
As of January 2026, the S&P Case-Shiller 20-City Index rose only 1.2% year-over-year — the weakest since July 2023. For 8 consecutive months, home price growth lagged consumer inflation, meaning real home values were declining. Regional divergence is stark: New York +4.9% versus Tampa −2.5%, illustrating why national averages can mislead. The tool's **[54 metro-specific defaults]** address this variation.

**Q46. What depreciation rate should I assume for housing?**
Poterba (1992) uses ~2% per year for owner-occupied housing physical depreciation. Combined with maintenance, total physical deterioration runs 2–3% of home value annually. Ben Felix and Statistics Canada use 2.1% of building value for depreciation plus maintenance combined. This hidden cost is often overlooked — it means a home must appreciate by 2–3% per year just to maintain its real value.

**Q47. How much should I budget for home maintenance?**
The 1% rule (1% of home value per year) is widely used but may be optimistic. Census Bureau data (2019) shows average actual spending of ~0.6%, but this likely reflects deferred maintenance. Financial advisors recommend budgeting 1–2% for newer homes and up to 4% for older homes (30+ years). Angi/HomeAdvisor data shows average annual upkeep at ~$3,192. The tool defaults to research-backed rates that users can adjust.

**Q48. What are total transaction costs for buying and selling a home?**
Round-trip costs total approximately **8–10% of home value**: real estate commissions (5–6% split between agents), plus closing costs on both ends (title insurance, escrow, transfer taxes, inspections, loan fees = another 2–5%). These are the largest single drag on housing returns for short holding periods. At a 7-year hold, 8% transaction costs eat 1.1% annually from returns.

**Q49. How have real estate commissions changed after the 2024 NAR settlement?**
Despite the $418 million NAR antitrust settlement (August 2024) that banned advertising buyer agent commissions on MLS, total commissions have not significantly declined. Redfin data shows buyer agent commissions at ~2.34% (Oct 2024), while total commissions average 5.5–5.7% nationally. The settlement primarily increased transparency through mandatory buyer representation agreements, but cost reduction has been modest so far.

**Q50. How much has homeowner's insurance increased recently?**
Dramatically. S&P Global reports national premiums rose 10.4% in 2024 following 12.7% in 2023. The Consumer Federation of America found a cumulative 24% increase from 2021–2024, with the typical annual premium reaching ~$3,303. Matic data shows a 2021 policyholder was paying 69% more by their 2024 renewal. Climate-affected states are far worse: Nebraska averages ~$6,400/year. These escalating costs increasingly favor renting.

**Q51. How much do property taxes vary across the US?**
Enormously. Effective rates range from **0.29% (Hawaii) to 2.47% (New Jersey)** — an 8.5× difference. Median annual bills range from $738 (Alabama) to $9,767 (New Jersey). The national average effective rate is ~0.89% with an average annual bill of ~$4,271 (NAHB, 2024). This tool includes **[metro-specific property tax defaults]** because using a national average in New Jersey or Hawaii would be misleading.

**Q52. What is Poterba's "user cost" of housing, and why does it matter?**
Poterba's formula (1984) captures the annual economic cost of ownership per dollar of house value: interest rate + property taxes + depreciation/maintenance − expected appreciation. For typical inputs (6% mortgage, 1.5% property tax, 2–3% depreciation, minus 3–4% appreciation), user cost runs 6–10% of home value annually. Tax deductions reduce this for itemizers, but with ~90% of filers taking the standard deduction, the subsidy is smaller than commonly assumed.

**Q53. Does homeownership build more wealth than renting and investing?**
It depends entirely on assumptions. Shiller's ~0.7% real appreciation versus the stock market's ~7% real return would seem to favor renting-and-investing. But housing has leverage (5:1 typical), imputed rent yield (3–5%), and forced savings. The total return including imputed rent makes housing more competitive (Jordà et al., 2019). The real question is behavioral: will you actually invest the difference? The **[renter discipline slider]** lets you model this honestly.

